---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';

const updated = '2026-04-26';
---
<Layout
  title="Privacy Policy — ConsentTheater"
  description="How ConsentTheater handles your data. Short version: we don't set tracking cookies, we don't run analytics, and we don't share anything."
>
  <section class="mx-auto w-full max-w-3xl px-6 pt-10 pb-12">
    <div class="mb-6">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground">
        Privacy
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-3xl">
        Privacy Policy
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-[11px] text-muted-foreground">
        Last updated <time datetime={updated} class="font-mono">{updated}</time>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-8 text-sm leading-relaxed text-foreground/90">
      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Short version</h2>
        <p>
          We run a tracker lookup — you type a cookie name or a domain, we tell you who's behind it.
          We don't set tracking cookies for marketing or advertising. We run anonymous,
          opt-in, self-hosted analytics (off by default). We don't share your data with
          anyone, because there is no personal data to share.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">What we store in your browser</h2>
        <p>
          Two storage entries — both qualify as <em>strictly necessary</em> under
          ePrivacy Art. 5(3) and require no consent:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-1.5 pl-6">
          <li>
            <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">ct_settings</code>
            <span class="text-muted-foreground"> · localStorage</span> — your theme,
            contrast and language preferences. Set when you change them in the
            settings panel. Never leaves your browser.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">zest_consent</code>
            <span class="text-muted-foreground"> · cookie, 365-day expiry, SameSite=Lax</span>
            — records the choice you made in the consent banner so we can honour
            it on subsequent visits. Set by
            <a href="https://zest.freshjuice.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">@freshjuice/zest</a>,
            our consent toolkit. Never leaves your browser.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-3">
          No fingerprinting, no session storage, no local databases. No third-party
          marketing or advertising scripts.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Analytics — opt-in only, first-party only</h2>
        <p>
          When you accept analytics through our consent banner, your browser sends a
          single
          <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">navigator.sendBeacon</code>
          to <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">/api/event</code> on
          this same origin. <strong>No third-party request, no cross-origin script,
          no external processor.</strong> The endpoint is part of the same Cloudflare
          Worker that serves the rest of this site, and it writes to a Cloudflare
          Analytics Engine dataset on our own account.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Analytics is <strong>off by default</strong>. Browsers sending <em>Do Not
          Track</em> or <em>Global Privacy Control</em> are treated as a default
          reject; you can still override that through the banner.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Each event records only path, page title (truncated), referrer host,
          country (derived from IP by Cloudflare's edge layer and never logged), and
          viewport class (mobile / tablet / desktop). The tracker sets no cookies,
          stores no IP, and uses no cross-site identifier. Cloudflare's Analytics
          Engine retains the raw events for 90 days.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          A public aggregate dashboard is on the roadmap once we're confident
          the dataset has settled — until then, the writes happen but no
          rendered dashboard is shipped on this site. The full list of fields
          collected is documented above, and the consent toggle is reachable
          from the <em>Cookie preferences</em> link in the footer at any time.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">What happens when you search</h2>
        <p>
          Every search issues a <code class="font-mono text-xs">GET /api/search?q=&hellip;</code>
          request to our edge endpoint. The endpoint runs on Cloudflare Workers. Your query is
          matched in memory against the Playbill — our tracker knowledge base — and the match (or
          an empty result) is returned. Queries are not persisted by us.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Cloudflare, our infrastructure provider, operates the edge network and may process
          standard request metadata (IP address, timestamp, user-agent, requested path) to route
          traffic and defend against abuse. Cloudflare's processing is governed by their
          <a
            href="https://www.cloudflare.com/privacypolicy/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="link"
          >privacy policy</a>.
          We do not access or retain those logs for analytics or marketing.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Legal basis &amp; your rights</h2>
        <p>
          Under the EU General Data Protection Regulation, the limited request metadata processed
          by our infrastructure provider is processed on the basis of legitimate interest
          (GDPR Art. 6(1)(f)) — specifically, keeping the service reachable and protecting it from
          abuse.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          You have the right to access, rectify, or erase data about you, to restrict or object to
          processing, to data portability, and to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority.
          Since we don't keep identifiable records of individual users, most of these rights are
          satisfied by default — but if you have a concrete request, email us (below) and we'll
          answer.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Browser extension</h2>
        <p>
          The ConsentTheater browser extension (Chrome / Firefox) is a separate piece of
          software from this website and has its own, more detailed privacy policy. The short
          version is the same: <strong>nothing leaves your browser</strong>. The extension has
          no server, no accounts, no telemetry, no analytics, and performs zero outbound
          requests to us during normal use. Scans only run when you click <em>Scan this page</em>.
          It never observes your regular browsing.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Full text and per-permission breakdown:
          <a
            href="https://github.com/ConsentTheater/extension/blob/main/PRIVACY.md"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="link"
          >extension privacy policy</a>.
          Overview and install links: see the
          <a href="/extension/" class="link">browser extension page</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Sub-processors</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-5">
          <li>
            <strong>Cloudflare, Inc.</strong> (101 Townsend Street, San Francisco, CA 94107, USA)
            — edge network, Workers runtime, and Analytics Engine.
            <ul class="mt-1 list-[circle] space-y-0.5 pl-5 text-xs">
              <li>
                Acts as our <strong>data processor</strong> under a signed
                <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-customer-dpa/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">
                  Cloudflare Data Processing Addendum (DPA)
                </a>.
              </li>
              <li>
                International transfers from the EU/UK to Cloudflare's US entities are covered
                by the
                <a href="https://www.dataprivacyframework.gov/list" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">
                  EU-US Data Privacy Framework
                </a>
                (Cloudflare is a self-certified active participant) and, as a fallback, by
                <a href="https://commission.europa.eu/law/law-topic/data-protection/international-dimension-data-protection/standard-contractual-clauses-scc_en" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">
                  Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)
                </a>
                where DPF does not apply.
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/privacypolicy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">Cloudflare's privacy policy</a>
                · <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/trust-hub/gdpr/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">GDPR resource hub</a>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          That's the whole list. If it ever grows, we'll update this page and note the change date
          at the top.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">International data transfers</h2>
        <p>
          ConsentTheater is operated from Berlin, Germany. The site, its API, and the
          first-party analytics dataset all run on Cloudflare's network. Practically:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-5">
          <li>
            <strong>Page requests are served from the nearest Cloudflare PoP</strong> to
            the visitor — for EU/UK visitors that's an EU/UK Point of Presence
            (Frankfurt, Amsterdam, London, Paris, etc.). The visitor's IP terminates at
            Cloudflare's edge, where the country code is derived. Our worker code
            receives the country code only — it never sees, logs, or stores the IP.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Analytics Engine</strong>, where the
            <code class="bg-secondary px-1 font-mono text-xs">/api/event</code> beacon
            writes its rows, is part of Cloudflare's globally-distributed Workers
            platform. Cloudflare does not currently offer EU-only data residency for
            Analytics Engine. The transfer to Cloudflare's US entities is therefore
            covered by the DPF / SCCs mechanism described above. Because the rows we
            write contain no personal data (no IP, no identifier, no cookie value), the
            substantive risk under GDPR Art. 44 et seq. is low — the transfer is of
            aggregate technical metadata, not data subjects' personal data.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Cloudflare's processing of the IP itself</strong> at the network
            layer (TLS termination, routing, DDoS / abuse defence) is carried out under
            <strong>Cloudflare's own legitimate-interest basis</strong> as a network
            operator (GDPR Art. 6(1)(f)), independent of any instruction from us.
            Cloudflare publishes a
            <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/trust-hub/abuse-approach/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">network-abuse policy</a>
            and a
            <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/transparency/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="link">transparency report</a>
            covering this layer.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
          If the EU-US Data Privacy Framework is ever invalidated by the CJEU (as
          Privacy Shield was in <em>Schrems II</em>), the SCCs fallback continues to
          apply and we will publish a notice on this page within 14 days. We do not
          rely on a single legal mechanism for international transfers; the redundancy
          is deliberate.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Changes</h2>
        <p>
          When we change this policy, the date at the top of the page changes. Material changes
          (new sub-processors, new categories of data collected) will be reflected in that date
          and summarised at the top of this section.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-2 font-display text-lg font-bold tracking-tight">Contact</h2>
        <p>
          Data controller: <strong>ConsentTheater</strong>.<br />
          Email:
          <a
            href="mailto:developer@consenttheater.org"
            class="link font-mono"
          >developer@consenttheater.org</a>
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
